Rating: 4
This recipe has become a standard part of the rotation at my house. I read the reviews and made some of the suggested changes. First of all, I just brown the pork on the stove and skip the baking step. For the sauce, I substitute Vidalia sweet onions for the shallots as I don't generally keep them on hand. I also add a couple of cloves of minced garlic. While cooking the onions and garlic, I add 1/4 tsp. of ground thyme per another cooks suggestion. I have prepared it with both a creamy Dijon and a more grainy mustard, both are good, but I do prefer the grainy mustard preparation. As recommended, I halved the amount of mustard and sometimes add a tbsp. of white wine or dry sherry as well. I also substitute balsamic vinegar for the lemon juice because I don't usually keep fresh lemons on hand in the winter. Be careful of the vinegar proportions, start with 1/2 tsp. and adjust as necessary. Because I love the sauce, I usually prepare a double batch.

